ions of assimilation, as many other studies have, this book concentrates on interethnic relations to provide an entirely new perspective on the changes wrought by immigration in the United States. A balanced analysis of Miami's evolution over the last forty years, This Land Is Our Land is also a powerful demonstration that immigration in America is not simply an "us versus them" phenomenon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCuban AmericansxSocial conditionsxFloridaxMiami. 0aCuban AmericanszFloridazMiamixSocial conditions. 0aElite (Social sciences)xFloridaxMiami. 0aElite (Social sciences)zFloridazMiami. 0aEthnic conflictxFloridaxMiami. 0aEthnic conflictzFloridazMiami. 0aImmigrantsxSocial conditionsxFloridaxMiami. 0aImmigrantszFloridazMiamixSocial conditions. 0aMinoritiesxSocial conditionsxFloridaxMiami. 0aMinoritieszFloridazMiamixSocial conditions. 0aPower (Social sciences)xFloridaxMiami. 0aPower (Social sciences)zFloridazMiami. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aCastro, Max, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGrenier, Guillermo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936461423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520936461.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles